LITERATURE_REVIEW = {
    "1.11 Literature Review": [
        "The academic literature on Human Resource Information Systems establishes that technology-enabled recruitment can significantly influence both process efficiency and perceived organisational professionalism. Laudon and Laudon (2020) emphasise that enterprise systems must align with business processes rather than forcing users to adapt to arbitrary software structures. This principle informed the decision to model interview workflows around actual GMB panel practices, including sequential candidate activation and external evaluator participation.",
        "Research on Applicant Tracking Systems by researchers in information systems highlights common functional modules: requisition management, candidate relationship management, interview scheduling, and compliance reporting. Commercial systems such as those offered by global HR technology vendors provide extensive integrations but may not accommodate local public-sector hiring conventions without expensive customisation. Open-source frameworks offer an alternative pathway for institutions willing to invest in bespoke development guided by structured analysis.",
        "Studies on curriculum vitae parsing and automated ranking demonstrate that text mining techniques including Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency (TF-IDF) vectorisation and cosine similarity can produce useful preliminary rankings when job descriptions contain explicit skill requirements. However, scholars caution against fully automated rejection decisions because semantic nuance, contextual experience, and non-standard career paths may be underrepresented in keyword models. The GMB system therefore treats automated scoring as decision support for HR reviewers who retain authority to advance or reject candidates manually.",
        "Literature on collaborative decision-making in hiring committees underscores the importance of aggregating independent judgements to reduce individual bias. Averaging normalised scores across multiple interviewers is a straightforward aggregation method comprehensible to audit stakeholders, though organisations may alternatively employ weighted averages or deliberative consensus sessions. The implemented system computes arithmetic means transparently displayed on HR mark sheets.",
        "Security literature relevant to web-based HR systems addresses authentication, authorisation, session hijacking prevention, and protection of personally identifiable information. Password hashing using PBKDF2 or bcrypt is widely recommended over reversible encryption or plaintext storage. Role-based access control models map organisational roles to permission sets; the GMB platform distinguishes HR managers, HR staff with granular screening and scoring permissions, interviewers with limited scoring rights on active candidates only, and audit users with read-oriented access.",
        "User experience research indicates that visual consistency and institutional branding on public careers pages influence applicant trust. Applicants associate polished interfaces with organisational competence. Conversely, broken links, unstyled forms, or non-responsive layouts may discourage qualified candidates from completing applications. The project's adoption of consistent teal, navy, and orange branding across applicant, HR, and interviewer portals responds to these findings.",
        "Finally, project management literature supports phased delivery and stakeholder engagement as predictors of information systems success. The structured chapter progression of this report mirrors classic waterfall phases while allowing iterative refinement within implementation. This hybrid approach is common in academic software engineering projects constrained by semester or term deadlines.",
    ],
}

